<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-112-620  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 112 620.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  March 1989 v14 n3 p245(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Learning the language.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wegner, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Simula, the first object-oriented language, was based uponclasses, co-routines, and subclasses, much as today'sobject-oriented languages are.andP;  An object has a set of operationsand can learn by experience because its state stores the effect ofoperations.andP;  A language which supports objects as languagefeatures is an object-based language.andP;  Some languages also haveclasses, templates which are used to create new objects.andO;Operations can be inherited from superclasses and inherited bysubclasses.andP;  One example of an inheritance hierarchy is studentsand females forming subclasses of person, which is itself asubclass of mammal.andP;  Object-oriented programming will becomeincreasingly important in the future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented LanguagesCritiqueProgram Development Techniques.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Objects, inheritance hierarchy, language evolution, types versusclasses (chart)Language references. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>